==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mesmerism
<hw>Mes"mer*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<persfn><etsep>Mesmer</etsep></persfn>, who first brought it into notice
at Vienna, about 1775: cf. F. <ets>mesm⟦eacute⟧risme</ets>.]</ety>
<def>An earlier name for <altname>hypnosis</altname> or
<altname>hypnotism</altname>, the art of inducing an extraordinary or
abnormal state of the nervous system, in which the actor claims to
control the actions, and communicate directly with the mind, of the
recipient. It is believed to be a state between sleep and wakefulness,
in which a person is more susceptible to suggestion than when awake. See
<cref>Animal magnetism</cref>, under <er>Magnetism</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerist</ent>⟦br⟧
